The paper deals with the computational complexity of finding stable outcomes in hedonic games, which is a topic in game theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). The paper also discusses the use of preference aggregation and voting schemes, which are topics in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and social choice theory (cs.SI). The paper uses graph theory to model the games, which falls under the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper discusses the tractability of computing stable outcomes, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.LG).
